Context:¶

According to the World Health Organization (WHO) stroke is the 2nd leading cause of death globally, responsible for approximately 11% of total deaths.

Problem Statement:¶

In this project, we use this dataset to predict whether a patient is likely to get a stroke or not based on our parameters.

Attribute Information:¶

  1. id: unique identifier
  2. gender: "Male", "Female" or "Other"
  3. age: age of the patient
  4. hypertension: 0 if the patient doesn't have hypertension, 1 if the patient has hypertension
  5. heart_disease: 0 if the patient doesn't have any heart diseases, 1 if the patient has a heart disease
  6. ever_married: "No" or "Yes"
  7. work_type: "children", "Govt_jov", "Never_worked", "Private" or "Self-employed"
  8. Residence_type: "Rural" or "Urban"
  9. avg_glucose_level: average glucose level in blood
  10. bmi: body mass index
  11. smoking_status: "formerly smoked", "never smoked", "smokes" or "Unknown"*
  12. stroke: 1 if the patient had a stroke or 0 if not

Data Pre-Processing¶

  • The bmi column has missing values. It is a numerical attribute, therefore we will imputate using the mean of each corresponding gender.
In [5]:
f_bmi = stroke_df[stroke_df['gender'] == 'Female'].mean()['bmi']
m_bmi = stroke_df[stroke_df['gender'] == 'Male'].mean()['bmi']

stroke_df[stroke_df['gender']=='Female'] = stroke_df[stroke_df['gender'] == 'Female'].fillna(f_bmi)
stroke_df[stroke_df['gender']=='Male'] = stroke_df[stroke_df['gender'] == 'Male'].fillna(m_bmi)
In [6]:
# initializing empty lists to store values in
cat_vars = []
num_vars = []
# looping through the dataframe
for col in stroke_df:
    # if categorical values, then store them in the cat_vars list
    if(stroke_df[col].dtype == 'object'):
        cat_vars.append(col)
    # if numerical
    elif(stroke_df[col].dtype in ('int64', 'float64')):
        # if unique values are less than 4, then append to the cat_vars list
        if(stroke_df[col].nunique() < 4):
            cat_vars.append(col)
        # if not, then store all the continuous data in the num_vars list
        else:
            num_vars.append(col)
# loop through the categorical values and print out the count for each category
for col in cat_vars:
    print(stroke_df[col].value_counts(), '\n')

In [7]:
stroke_df = stroke_df[stroke_df.gender != 'Other']
stroke_df = stroke_df[stroke_df.work_type != 'Never_worked']
# Removing "unknown" smoking status
stroke_df['smoking_status'].replace('Unknown', np.nan, inplace=True)
# Getting the mode for smoking status if null
stroke_df['smoking_status'].fillna(stroke_df['smoking_status'].mode()[0], inplace=True)

Mapping and Dummy Variables¶

In [11]:
# mappings for marriage, residence type, and gender
ever_married_mappings = {'No':0,'Yes':1}
Residence_type_mappings = {'Rural':0, 'Urban':1}
gender_mappings = {'Male':0, 'Female':1}

# apply mappings
stroke_df['ever_married'] = stroke_df['ever_married'].map(ever_married_mappings)
stroke_df['Residence_type'] = stroke_df['Residence_type'].map(Residence_type_mappings)
stroke_df['gender'] = stroke_df['gender'].map(gender_mappings)

# Dummy variables for encoding
encoded_columns = ['work_type', 'smoking_status']
stroke_df = pd.get_dummies(stroke_df, encoded_columns, drop_first=True)

Resampling and Create/Train Model¶

In [12]:
# IMPORT LIBRARIES
%matplotlib inline
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

# X is all attributes that are not stroke
X = stroke_df.drop('stroke', axis=1)
# y is just the stroke column
y = stroke_df['stroke']

fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2, figsize=(15,5))
sns.countplot(ax=axes[0], x=y).set(title='Before Oversampling')

# we have to resample the data here because there is a significant amount of difference of those who did have a stroke and who didn't
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE
sm = SMOTE(random_state=42)
X, y = sm.fit_resample(X, y)
# plotting the amount after resampling
sns.countplot(ax=axes[1], x=y).set(title='After Oversampling')
plt.show()

Part I. K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) - Holdout method and repeated sampling¶

In [16]:
# import library
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
# we can only have 2 clusters - individual has a stroke or they do not
clf_1 = KNeighborsClassifier(2)
clf_1.fit(X_train, y_train)

# random sampling
rng = np.random.RandomState(seed=12345)
seeds = np.arange(10**5)
rng.shuffle(seeds)
seeds = seeds[:50]

pred_2 = []

for i in seeds:
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.5, random_state=i, stratify=y)
    y_pred_i = clf_1.fit(X_train, y_train).predict(X_test)
    y_pred_i_acc = np.mean(y_test == y_pred_i)
    pred_2.append(y_pred_i_acc)
pred_2 = np.asarray(pred_2)
print('Average: %.2f%%' % (pred_2.mean()*100))

# plotting accuracy vs repetition graph
with plt.style.context(('fivethirtyeight')):
    plt.bar(range(0, pred_2.shape[0]), pred_2, color='gray', alpha=0.7)
    plt.axhline(pred_2.max(), color='k', linewidth=1, linestyle='--')
    plt.axhline(pred_2.min(), color='k', linewidth=1, linestyle='--')
    plt.axhspan(pred_2.min(), pred_2.max(), alpha=0.2, color='steelblue')
    plt.ylim([0, pred_2.max() + 0.1])
    plt.xlabel('Repetition')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.ylim([0.5, 1.05])
    plt.tight_layout()
    #plt.savefig('figures/model-eval-iris_0.svg')
    plt.show()

Average: 90.58%

Part II. Logistic Regression - Pessimistic Bias in Holdout¶

In [19]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

clf_2 = LogisticRegression(penalty='l2',
                            dual=False,
                            tol=0.0001,
                            C=0.000001,
                            fit_intercept=True,
                            intercept_scaling=1,
                            class_weight=None,
                            random_state=12,
                            solver='lbfgs',
                            max_iter=1000,
                            multi_class='multinomial',
                            verbose=0,
                            warm_start=False,
                            n_jobs=1)
pred_train, pred_test = [], []

intervals = np.arange(500, X_train.shape[0] + 1, 200)

for i in intervals:
    clf_2.fit(X_train2[:i], y_train2[:i])
    p_train = clf_2.score(X_train2[:i], y_train2[:i])
    p_test = clf_2.score(X_test2, y_test2)
    pred_train.append(p_train)
    pred_test.append(p_test)
    
with plt.style.context(('fivethirtyeight')):
    plt.plot(intervals, pred_train, marker='o', label='Train')
    plt.plot(intervals, pred_test, marker='s', label='Test')
    plt.legend(loc='best', numpoints=1)
#   plt.xlim([430, X_train2.shape[0] + X_test.shape[0]])
    plt.xlim([2300,2900])
    plt.axvspan(X_train2.shape[0],
                X_train2.shape[0] + X_test.shape[0],
                alpha=0.2,
                color='steelblue')
    plt.ylim([0.763, 0.78])
    plt.xlabel('Training Set Size')
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.tight_layout()

                            weights='uniform',

                            p=2,
                            metric='minkowski',
                            metric_params=None,
                            n_jobs=1)

idx = np.arange(y.shape[0])

for i in range(200):

#     test_idx = np.setdiff1d(idx, train_idx, assume_unique=False)

#     boot_train_X, boot_train_y = X[train_idx], y[train_idx]
#     boot_test_X, boot_test_y = X[test_idx], y[test_idx]
    boot_train_X, boot_test_X, boot_train_y, boot_test_y = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=i)
    
    clf.fit(boot_train_X, boot_train_y)
    acc = clf.score(boot_test_X, boot_test_y)
    accuracies.append(acc)
In [23]:
mean = np.mean(accuracies)

#se = np.sqrt( (1. / (100-1)) * np.sum([(acc - mean)**2 for acc in ,accuracies]))
#ci = 1.984 * se

se = np.sqrt( (1. / (200-1)) * np.sum([(acc - mean)**2 for acc in accuracies]))
ci = 1.97 * se

lower = np.percentile(accuracies, 2.5)
upper = np.percentile(accuracies, 97.5)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 4))
ax.vlines(mean, [0], 80, lw=2.5, linestyle='-', label='mean')

ax.vlines(upper, [0], 15, lw=2.5, linestyle='-.')

ax.vlines(mean + ci, [0], 15, lw=2.5, linestyle=':', label='CI95 standard')

#ax.vlines(med, [0], 60, lw=2.5, linestyle='--', label='median')
ax.vlines(lower, [0], 15, lw=2.5, linestyle='-.', label='CI95 percentile')
ax.vlines(upper, [0], 15, lw=2.5, linestyle='-.')

ax.vlines(mean + ci, [0], 15, lw=2.5, linestyle=':', label='CI95 standard')
ax.vlines(mean - ci, [0], 15, lw=2.5, linestyle=':')

ax.hist(accuracies, bins=11,
        color='#0080ff', edgecolor="none",
        alpha=0.3)
plt.legend(loc='upper left')

#plt.xlim([0.55, .75])
plt.tight_layout()
